properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Locations: southern New Brunswick. Time span: early Sunday morning until early Sunday evening. Remarks: showers or periods of rain will continue tonight then change to freezing rain early Sunday morning and then change over or mix with ice pellets for more central areas Sunday afternoon as temperatures fall rapidly during the day. For the Fundy region and southwestern areas, precipitation on Sunday is expected to fall primarily as freezing rain with significant accretion expected. Additional rainfall amounts tonight: 10 to 15 mm. Ice pellets accumulations on Sunday: 5 to 10 cm. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain and warm temperatures for tonight followed by freezing rain, rain and ice pellets on Sunday. Total rainfall: 10-30 mm tonight and Sunday. Freezing rain: significant ice accretion likely overnight tonight into Sunday, with the most accretion expected over parts of the Annapolis Valley and central and eastern areas of mainland Nova Scotia. Freezing rain is expected to end Sunday evening. Winds: gusts to 80 km/h in the Tantramar Marsh region this evening. Gusts of 40 km/h on Sunday over northern areas. Locations: Nova Scotia, excluding southwesternmost regions and northern Cape Breton. Remarks: rain and very mild temperatures associated with brisk southwest winds can be expected this evening. Temperatures will fall rapidly overnight tonight over northern areas of the province and over most other areas of the province early on Sunday morning. Rain will change to freezing rain or ice pellets over much of the province by early Sunday morning. These conditions are expected to persist throughout the day Sunday, although some areas along the Atlantic coast will change to rain as temperatures rise somewhat on Sunday afternoon. Significant impacts from these changing precipitation types are likely. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: 5 to 20 cm of snow by Sunday afternoon. Another low pressure system with a cool airmass will bring a second round of snow to the Lower Mainland beginning this evening. Once again, higher elevations such as West Vancouver, North Vancouver and Coquitlam will see the greatest snow accumulations near 20 cm by Sunday afternoon. Vancouver, Burnaby and New Westminster will see wet snow mixed with rain. Precipitation type will depend on proximity to the water, elevation, intensity and wind direction. As a result, lower accumulations of 5 to 10 cm are forecast for these cities. Some uncertainty remains for Surrey and Langley as southerly winds are forecast to develop overnight which may moderate temperatures and keep precipitation as rain or a mix of rain and snow such that accumulations are reduced. However, over the northern sections near Fraser Height, snow accumulations near 5 cm are possible. Richmond, Delta, Tsawwassen and Ladner are more likely to be influenced by the southerly winds tonight, keeping temperatures warm enough to see mostly rain. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A multi-day episode of very cold wind chills is expected. Extremely cold temperatures with wind chills below -50 have redeveloped this evening. The extreme cold conditions will moderate south of Great Slave Lake and the Mackenzie River tomorrow morning as a weak system brings some cloud and light snow. However, regions north of Great Slave Lake will remain in extreme cold conditions for the next few days, and wind chills could approach -60 at times in areas north of Yellowknife. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Snow, mixed with ice pellets and possibly briefly with some freezing rain will continue tonight. Description: Snowfall with total amounts of about 15 cm is expected. Northwestern edge of snow storm affecting the region tonight into Sunday. properties.Title: Arctic Outflow Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Very strong outflow winds and severely cold wind chill values are expected or occurring. A prolonged period of frigid temperatures, strong arctic outflow winds and low wind chill values will begin tonight. An arctic ridge of high pressure is building over the BC Interior and pushing towards the coast tonight. Strong outflow winds are expected to develop this evening, driving arctic air through mainland valleys and inlets. Temperatures will make a significant drop tonight, with wind chill values falling to at least -20. These frigid conditions are expected to persist well into next week. ### Frostbite and hypothermia can occur within minutes if adequate precautions are not taken when outdoors. Arctic outflow warnings are issued when bitterly cold air flows from the interior to coastal communities and the outflow winds create wind chill values of -20 or less for 6 hours or more. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
